answers.body_markdown:
---

*Disclaimer: Design of very efficient data structures it is something strictly related to the domain (architecture) and the context of the data. The following solution aims to be theoretically efficient for the general case. See final considerations for more details.*

---

### Structure Design

The idea is simple.

Keep an *underlying data structure* which represents the *queue*.

Every time a new event is inserted, check if the type is already present. In that case, we can delete that element. In such a way, we maintain the first property (only one instance per type, and that implies we always pop the most-recent for that type).

Finally, we insert the new instance at the end of the queue. Therefore, we keep the second property.


---
### An example of simple Implementation

    #include &lt;algorithm&gt;
    #include &lt;list&gt;
    #include &lt;utility&gt;
    
    class QueueWithAGoodName {
     public:
      using reference = Event&amp;;
    
      void push(Event event) {
        if (const auto finder =
                std::find_if(queue_.begin(),
                             queue_.end(),
                             [eventType = event.type](const Event&amp; event) {
                               return event.type == eventType;
                             });
            finder != queue_.end()) {
          queue_.erase(finder);
        }
        queue_.push_back(std::move(event));
      }
    
      reference front() { return queue_.front(); }
    
      void pop() { queue_.pop_front(); }
    
     private:
      std::list&lt;Event&gt; queue_;
    };

[Live Example](https://godbolt.org/z/qlkTbZ)

---

### Considerations and Analysis

* For my example, I have used a `std::list` as the *underlying data structure*. Indeed, a `std::list` is handy in case you have frequent deletion &quot;in the middle&quot;. Moreover, after deletion, iterators are not invalidated. That&#39;s a good property in case we want to improve our queue.

* `QueueWithAGoodName::push` has a runtime time complexity: `O(N)` (because we apply a linear scan for finding the type). Where `N` is the size of the queue.
* `QueueWithAGoodName::pop` and `QueueWithAGoodName::front` are `O(1)`.

### Further Considerations
* For such type of data structure, there is an important property. We have one instance per type. That implies `N` (the size of the queue) is upper-bounded by the number of `EventType`s.
* If the number of event types is limited, several considerations can be applied because (for common architectures) the runtime complexity `O(N)` can be approximate as `O(1)`. In such case, `std::vector` as underlying data-structure is probably more efficient because of caches.
* In the simple example I&#39;ve reported, `push` is `O(N)`. In case you have several types of `EventType`s you can make the data structure more efficient in the push operation. In short, you can use an auxiliary `std::unordered_map&lt;EventType, list::iterator&gt;` (that is, an *hash map*) to avoid the linear search. After erasing, `std::list` does not invalidate iterators, so the hash table remains consistent.

