I’m relatively new to Python, and I come from a language (Java) with a very different outlook on OOP. I understand most of the times how to do things in Python that I used to do in Java, but I’m still struggling with the new philosophy. In particular, I’m not sure I fully understand inheritance and instantiation. I’m going to write below what’s my current understanding of these two notions in Python: **please correct me if what I say is wrong, confirm it if it is right, or add whatever clarification you feel is needed.**

(1)	Inheritance is a relationship between objects (not between classes), if an object `obj1` inherit from an object `obj2`, and the mention of an attribute `attr` can’t be resolved in the namespace of `obj1`, Python will try to resolve `attr` in the namespace of `obj2` (that is `obj1.attr` become virtually `obj2.attr`). And this is it. There is no other semantics attached to the concept of inheritance.

(2)	When we define a class with code of the form `class A(B): … `, `A` doesn’t really inherit `B` (that is the class-object `A` we create doesn’t inherit the class-object `B` in the sense of (1)). This statement only specifies that an instance of `A` will inherit `B`. So, for example, from the code of `A`, we won’t have any access to static methods of `B` (unless we reach them by an enclosing or global scope).

(3)	An instantiation is a form of inheritance, the code `x = A()` create an object `x` which inherit classes `A` and `B` (in this order, in the sense of (1)).

In brief, instantiation is inheritance (this was really hard for me to accept), and classes (i.e. class-objects) don’t inherit, their instances do.

